\begin_layout Subsection
Law of reflection
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The law of reflection is the statement that the angle of reflection 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{r}$
\end_inset

 of the wave, due to its scattering as it impinges on a flat surface, is
 equal to its angle of incidence 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\theta_{i}=\theta_{r}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

A simple derivation of this law can be found in [1].
 Both of these angles are measured with respect to the normal of the surface
 that performs the reflection of the wave.
 Note that this law applies only when the mirror is large compared to the
 wavelength of the wave, enabling the electrons at the surface to oscillate
 in phase with each other when they absorb and emit the energy carried by
 the wave.
 In the context of this project, this condition holds, so we expect the
 law of reflection to apply.
\end_layout

