\begin_layout Standard
Snell's Law relates the refractive indices of two media to the respective
 incident and transmitted angles of a ray of light as it propagates from
 one medium to the other.
 Let the refractive index of the originating medium be 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i}$
\end_inset

 and the refractive index of the medium into which the wave propagates be
 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{t}$
\end_inset

, and let the incident and transmitted angles at the interface be 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{t}$
\end_inset

, respectively, and according to Snell's Law
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
n_{i}\sin\theta_{i}=n_{r}\sin\theta_{t}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We see that the law of reflection can be recovered from this statement,
 since in the case of reflection, 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i}=n_{r}$
\end_inset

, and thus it follows that the incidence angle is equal to the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

transmitted
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 angle, which in this case is the reflected angle.
 A proper derivation of Snell's Law can be found in [1].
 Note that the refractive index 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 of a material is related to the speed of light in vacuum 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 and the speed of light in the medium 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
n=\frac{c}{v}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which implies that light travels at different velocities in different media.
 The refractive index of air 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{air}\approx1$
\end_inset

, a fact that will be used extensively throughout this work.
 In the second experiment of this report, we will use Snell's Law and the
 geometry shown in Figure 1 in order to find the refractive index of water
 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{w}$
\end_inset

.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{mt}=d_{mw}+d_{wt}$
\end_inset

, and we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\theta_{i}=\arctan\left(\frac{a}{d_{mt}}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\theta_{t}=\arctan\left(\frac{b-c}{d_{wt}}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The rules for similar triangles allow us to write 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
c=\frac{ad_{mw}}{d_{mt}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

By Snell's law, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
n_{w}=\frac{n_{air}\sin\theta_{i}}{\sin\theta_{t}}=\frac{\sin\theta_{i}}{\sin\theta_{t}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Combining equations (4)-(7) gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
n_{w} & = & \frac{\sin\left[\arctan\left(\frac{a}{d_{mt}}\right)\right]}{\sin\left[\arctan\left(\frac{b}{d_{wt}}-\frac{ad_{mw}}{d_{wt}d_{mt}}\right)\right]}\nonumber \\
 & = & \frac{a}{bd_{mt}-ad_{mw}}\sqrt{\frac{\left(bd_{mt}-ad_{mw}\right)^{2}+d_{mt}^{2}d_{wt}^{2}}{a^{2}+d_{mt}^{2}}}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


