\begin_layout Standard
The index of refraction 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 of a transparent triangular prism can be calculated by determining the
 angle of minimum deviation 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{min}$
\end_inset

, which can be derived from the geometry of Figure 2.
 From the figure, it can be seen that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 and the angles 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{3}$
\end_inset

 are related by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
(90^{\circ}-\theta_{2})+\varepsilon+(90^{\circ}-\theta_{3})=180\textdegree
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\varepsilon=\theta_{2}+\theta_{3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Whereas the angle of deviation 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta=(\theta_{1}-\theta_{2})+(\theta_{4}-\theta_{3})=\theta_{1}+\theta_{4}-\varepsilon
\end{equation}

\end_inset

By symmetry, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{min}$
\end_inset

 must occur when 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{1}=\theta_{4}$
\end_inset

, which in turn implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{2}=\theta_{3}$
\end_inset

, which means that equations (10) and (11) become
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\varepsilon & = & 2\theta_{2}\\
\delta_{min} & = & 2\theta_{1}-\varepsilon
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Using Snell's Law and taking into account that the medium to either side
 of the prism is air, we have that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\sin\theta_{1} & = & n\sin\theta_{2}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Solving for 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, and using equations (12) and (13), we obtain a way for calculating the
 refractive index of the prism
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
n=\frac{\sin\left(\frac{\delta_{min}+\varepsilon}{2}\right)}{\sin\left(\frac{\varepsilon}{2}\right)}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

