\begin_layout Standard
The phenomenon of total internal reflection occurs when a ray of light propagati
ng from a medium with refractive index 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i}$
\end_inset

 into a medium with refractive index 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{t}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i}>n_{t}$
\end_inset

 is completely reflected back towards the original medium, that is, the
 transmitted intensity of the beam is equal to zero.
 The minimum angle at which this happens is known as the critical angle
 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{i}=\theta_{c}$
\end_inset

, for which 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{t}=90^{\circ}$
\end_inset

.
 By Snell's Law,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sin\theta_{i}=\frac{n_{t}}{n_{i}}\sin\theta_{t}\rightarrow\sin\theta_{c}=\frac{n_{t}}{n_{i}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In the present experiment, 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i}=n$
\end_inset

 will be the refractive index of a 
\begin_inset Formula $90^{\circ}$
\end_inset

 transparent glass prism, and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{t}=n_{air}$
\end_inset

, so (18) becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sin\theta_{c}=\frac{1}{n}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Now let a beam of light impinge on one of the faces of the prism with an
 angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{c}$
\end_inset

 as depicted in Figure 4.
 The geometry of the setup gives the following equation relating the angles
 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{c}'$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{c}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\varepsilon-\phi_{c}'-\theta_{c}=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset

By Snell's law, we have that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sin\phi_{c}'=\frac{\sin\phi_{c}}{n}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Combining equations (19)-(21) gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{1}{n}=\sin(\varepsilon-\phi_{c}')=\sin\left[\varepsilon-\arcsin\left(\frac{\sin\phi_{c}}{n}\right)\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Applying the trigonometric identities 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin(a-b)=\sin(a)\cos(b)-\cos(a)\sin(b)$
\end_inset

 allows us to write
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{1}{n} & = & \sin\varepsilon\cos\left[\arcsin\left(\frac{\sin\phi_{c}}{n}\right)\right]-\cos\varepsilon\sin\left[\arcsin\left(\frac{\sin\phi_{c}}{n}\right)\right]\nonumber \\
 & = & \sin\varepsilon\cos\left[\arcsin\left(\frac{\sin\phi_{c}}{n}\right)\right]-\frac{\cos\varepsilon\sin\phi_{c}}{n}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

 And since 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\left[\arcsin\left(a\right)\right]=\sqrt{1-a^{2}}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{n}=\sin\varepsilon\sqrt{1-\frac{\sin^{2}\phi_{c}}{n^{2}}}-\frac{\cos\varepsilon\sin\phi_{c}}{n}
\]

\end_inset

Some further elementary algebra yields the following expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{2}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
n^{2}=\sin^{2}\phi_{c}+\left(\frac{1+\cos\varepsilon\sin\phi_{c}}{\sin\varepsilon}\right)^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Expanding the square of the expression in parenthesis and adding yields
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
n^{2} & = & \frac{1+2\cos\varepsilon\sin\phi_{c}+\cos^{2}\varepsilon\sin^{2}\phi_{c}+\sin^{2}\varepsilon\sin^{2}\phi_{c}}{\sin^{2}\varepsilon}\\
 & = & \frac{1+2\cos\varepsilon\sin\phi_{c}+\sin^{2}\phi_{c}\left(\cos^{2}\varepsilon+\sin^{2}\varepsilon\right)}{\sin^{2}\varepsilon}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Finally, using the identity 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos^{2}a+\sin^{2}a=1$
\end_inset

 gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
n^{2} & = & \frac{\cos^{2}\varepsilon+\sin^{2}\varepsilon+2\cos\varepsilon\sin\phi_{c}+\sin^{2}\phi_{c}}{\sin^{2}\varepsilon}\nonumber \\
 & = & 1+\frac{\cos^{2}\varepsilon+2\cos\varepsilon\sin\phi_{c}+\sin^{2}\phi_{c}}{\sin^{2}\varepsilon}\nonumber \\
n & = & \sqrt{1+\left(\frac{\cos\varepsilon+\sin\phi_{c}}{\sin\varepsilon}\right)^{2}}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Reflectivity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The reflectivity 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 of an interface is defined as the ratio of the intensities of the reflected
 wave and the incident wave, 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{r}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{0}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
R=\frac{I_{0}}{I_{r}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The relationship between a material's refraction index and it's reflection
 coefficient, assuming the material is surrounded by air, can be derived
 as follows.
 An electromagnetic wave incident on the material is, in general, reflected
 and refracted, with part of the wave's energy being transmitted into the
 material, and part of it being reflected back towards the original medium
 from which it came from.
 For a wave polarized in such a way that the electric field 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{E}$
\end_inset

 is perpendicular to the plane of incidence, the tangential components of
 the electric field at either side of the interface are continuous, or in
 other words,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\vec{E}_{0i}+\vec{E}_{0r}=\vec{E}_{0t}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the quantities on the left hand side are the magnitudes of the incident
 and reflected electric fields, respectively, and the one on the right hand
 side is the magnitude of the transmitted electric field.
 The electric field is related to the magnetic field 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{B}$
\end_inset

 via
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{k}\times\vec{E}=v\vec{B}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{k}$
\end_inset

 is a unit vector pointing in the direction of propagation, and 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is the velocity of the wave.
 This implies that the magnetic field of the wave points parallel to the
 interface.
 Ampere's Law provides another equation by demanding that the tangential
 component of 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\vec{B}}{\mu}$
\end_inset

 be continuous across the two media.
 The constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is the magnetic permeability of the material.
 This implies that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{-B_{i}}{\mu_{i}}\cos\theta_{i}+\frac{B_{r}}{\mu_{i}}\cos\theta_{r}=\frac{-B_{t}}{\mu_{t}}\cos\theta_{t}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which, when combined with equation (27), yields
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{1}{\mu_{i}v_{i}}(E_{i}-E_{r})\cos\theta_{i}=\frac{1}{\mu_{t}v_{t}}E_{t}\cos\theta_{t}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using equation (3) and the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{E}=\vec{E}_{0}e^{i(\vec{k}\cdot\vec{r}-\omega t)}$
\end_inset

, we can write
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{n_{i}}{\mu_{i}}(E_{0i}-E_{0r})\cos\theta_{i}=\frac{n_{t}}{\mu_{t}}E_{0t}\cos\theta_{t}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

combined with equation (30), we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\frac{E_{0r}}{E_{0i}}\right)_{\perp}=\frac{\frac{n_{i}}{\mu_{i}}\cos\theta_{i}-\frac{n_{t}}{\mu_{t}}\cos\theta_{t}}{\frac{n_{i}}{\mu_{i}}\cos\theta_{i}+\frac{n_{t}}{\mu_{t}}\cos\theta_{t}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An analysis along the same lines allows us to calculate the same ratio for
 the case of the electric field being parallel to the plane of incidence,
 which is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\frac{E_{0r}}{E_{0i}}\right)_{\parallel}=\frac{\frac{n_{t}}{\mu_{i}}\cos\theta_{i}-\frac{n_{i}}{\mu_{t}}\cos\theta_{t}}{\frac{n_{t}}{\mu_{i}}\cos\theta_{i}+\frac{n_{i}}{\mu_{t}}\cos\theta_{t}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the case of transition between air and glass, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{i}\approx\mu_{t}\approx\mu_{0}$
\end_inset

, and the equations simplify to
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\left(\frac{E_{0r}}{E_{0i}}\right)_{\perp} & = & \frac{n_{i}\cos\theta_{i}-n_{t}\cos\theta_{t}}{n_{i}\cos\theta_{i}+n_{t}\cos\theta_{t}}\\
\left(\frac{E_{0r}}{E_{0i}}\right)_{\parallel} & = & \frac{n_{t}\cos\theta_{i}-n_{i}\cos\theta_{t}}{n_{t}\cos\theta_{i}+n_{i}\cos\theta_{t}}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The reflectivities 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\perp}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\parallel}$
\end_inset

 correspond to the square of these equations, because the intensity of the
 wave corresponds to the squared magnitude of the electric field.
 For the case of normal incidence, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{i}=\theta_{t}=90^{\circ}$
\end_inset

, and using 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i}=n_{air}=1,$
\end_inset

 we have that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
R_{\perp}=R_{\parallel}=\left(\frac{1-n}{1+n}\right)^{2}=\left(\frac{n-1}{n+1}\right)^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, we have that for unpolarized light, 
\begin_inset Formula $R=\frac{1}{2}\left(R_{\perp}+R_{\parallel}\right)$
\end_inset

, and thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
R=\left(\frac{n-1}{n+1}\right)^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

