\begin_layout Standard
In the third part of the experiment, we use two different setups in order
 to be able to calculate the reflectivity of the prism, 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Starting with the arrangement from Part B, we now place the photosensor
 90 degrees from where it was, and place the mirror in the photosensor's
 original position.
 We then measure the intensity 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1}$
\end_inset

 of the light that reaches the photosensor in this setup.
 Next, we perform the same procedure but with the prism instead of the mirror,
 and measure an intensity 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 A naive analysis of the optical system would suggest that the equations
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{2}$
\end_inset

 would be
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
I_{1} & = & I_{0}T_{bs}R_{m}R_{bs}\\
I_{2} & = & I_{0}T_{bs}R_{p}R_{bs}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{m}$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the reflectivity of the flat mirror, and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{bs}$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the reflectivity of the mirror when the beam is incident
 from the right.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A more careful examination, however, leads to the conclusion that equation
 (42) is incorrect.
 Due to the geometry of the prism, when the beam strikes one of its shorter
 sides at normal incidence, the transmitted wave undergoes a double reflection
 with the two other sides that adds to the intensity of the light reflected
 by the first air/glass interface.
 Let the incident beam have an intensity 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{i}$
\end_inset

, and we have that the reflected intensity 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{r}$
\end_inset

 is actually given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
I_{r}=2R_{p}I_{i}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this case, 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{i}=I_{0}T_{bs}$
\end_inset

, which implies that the correct expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{2}$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
I_{2}=2I_{0}T_{bs}R_{p}R_{bs}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Combining equations (41) and (44) and solving for 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{p}$
\end_inset

 gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
R_{p}=\frac{I_{2}R_{m}}{2I_{1}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which illustrates why part B of this experiment was unnecessary.
 Now we can apply equation (37) and solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{p}$
\end_inset

, which gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
n=\frac{-1-R_{p}\pm2\sqrt{R_{p}}}{R_{p}-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The sign ambiguity is inevitable, but in practice we end up using the negative
 sign because otherwise we get a value of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 that is less than unity.
\end_layout

