\begin_layout Subsection
Procedures for data reduction and error analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We use two different approaches to reducing the data measured.
 In the case of the experiments in which we can gather multiple data points,
 we apply the orthogonal distance regression (ODR) module of the Python
 library SciPy [3].
 This is a good way of accounting for the fact that our measurements have
 errors in both the dependent and the independent variables.
 The idea behind this algorithm is to minimize the merit function
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\chi^{2}=\sum_{i=0}^{N-1}\left[\frac{y_{i}-\sum_{k=0}^{M-1}f(x_{i},\vec{p})}{\sigma_{xi}^{2}+\sigma_{yi}^{2}}\right]^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the measured value of the dependent variable, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the independent variable,
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{xi}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{yi}$
\end_inset

 a measure of their their standard deviations (taken to be their measurement
 error), and 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x_{i},\vec{p})$
\end_inset

 an arbitrary model function of the independent variables and a vector of
 parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{p}$
\end_inset

.
 ODR is based on the Levenberg-Marquardt method described in [4], and this
 particular implementation is able to provide a best fit and a standard
 deviation for the values of the parameters in the model, which we will
 identify with the values of the quantities that we are trying to calculate
 from the experiment, as will be seen below.
 A more detailed examination of ODR is beyond the scope of this work and
 can be found in [5].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the cases in which we have only one (experiment 3) or two (experiment
 5) data points, we calculate the value of the quantity that we are trying
 to find simply by writing it in terms of the dependent and independent
 variables and applying error propagation.
 In the particular case of experiment 5, we calculate the two values for
 the refractive index independently.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In both cases we use the Python uncertainties package [6] in order to perform
 error propagation.
 This package allows us to calculate errors for complicated expressions
 that depend on the measured experimental quantities, whose errors we estimate
 from the practical difficulty of the corresponding measurement and the
 precision of the instrument used in order to perform it.
\end_layout

